[src:p-adic-analysis/hensel-s-lemma] Completeness of a ring is not a necessary condition for the ring to have the Henselian property: Goro Azumaya in 1950 defined a commutative local ring satisfying the Henselian property for the maximal ideal **m** to be a **Henselian ring**.
[src:p-adic-analysis/hensel-s-lemma] Masayoshi Nagata proved in the 1950s that for any commutative local ring *A* with maximal ideal **m** there always exists a smallest ring *A*h containing *A* such that *A*h is Henselian with respect to **m***A*h.
[src:p-adic-analysis/hensel-s-lemma] This *A*h is called the **Henselization** of *A*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/hensel-s-lemma] If *A* is noetherian, *A*h will also be noetherian, and *A*h is manifestly algebraic as it is constructed as a limit of étale neighbourhoods.
[src:p-adic-analysis/hensel-s-lemma] This means that *A*h is usually much smaller than the completion *Â* while still retaining the Henselian property and remaining in the same category.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] In mathematics, a **local field** is a locally compact Hausdorff non-discrete topological field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Local fields find many applications in algebraic number theory, where they arise naturally as completions of global fields.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Moreover, tools like integration and Fourier analysis are available for functions defined on local fields.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Given a local field, an absolute value can be defined on it which gives rise to a complete metric that generates its topology.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] There are two basic types of local field: those called **Archimedean local fields** in which the absolute value is Archimedean, and those called **non-Archimedean local fields** in which it is not.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Non-Archimedean local fields can also be defined as those fields which are complete with respect to a metric induced by a discrete valuation whose residue field is finite.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Given a local field F , a "module function" on F can be defined as follows.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] First, consider the additive group of the field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] As a locally compact topological group, it has a unique (up to positive scalar multiple) Haar measure $\mu$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] The module of an element a of F is defined so as to measure the change in size of a set after multiplying it by a .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] for any measurable subset X of F (with $0<\mu (X)<\infty$ ).
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] This module does not depend on X nor on the choice of Haar measure $\mu$ (since the same scalar multiple ambiguity will occur in both the numerator and the denominator).
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] for some constant A that only depends on F .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Using $\operatorname {mod} _{K}$ , one may then define an absolute value $|\cdot |$ on F that induces a metric d on F (by setting $d(x,y)=|x-y|$ ), such that F is complete with respect to this metric, and the metric induces the given topology on F .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Every non-zero element a of F can be written as $a=\varpi ^{n}u$ with u a unit in ${\mathcal {O}}^{\times }$ , and n a unique integer.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] The **normalized valuation** of F is the surjective function $v:F\to \mathbb {Z} \cup \{\infty \}$ defined by sending a non-zero a to the unique integer n such that $a=\varpi ^{n}u$ with u a unit, and by sending 0 to $\infty$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] An equivalent and very important definition of a non-Archimedean local field is that it is a field that is complete with respect to a discrete valuation and whose residue field is finite.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] The group $U^{(1)}$ is called the **group of principal units**.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] where q is the order of the residue field, and $\mu _{q-1}$ is the group of ( $q-1$ )-st roots of unity in F .
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] The definition for "local field" adopted in this article, as a locally compact Hausdorff non-discrete topological field, is common today.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Some authors however reserve the term "local field" for what we have called "non-Archimedean local field".
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Research papers in modern number theory often consider a more general notion of non-Archimedean local field, requiring only that they be complete with respect to a discrete valuation and that the residue field be perfect of positive characteristic, not necessarily finite.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] In his book *Local Fields*, Serre defines "local fields" as fields that are complete with respect to a discrete valuation, without any restriction on the residue field, leading to a notion that is more general still.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] A local field is sometimes called a *one-dimensional local field*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] A non-Archimedean local field can be viewed as the field of fractions of the completion of the local ring of a one-dimensional arithmetic scheme of rank 1 at its non-singular point.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] For a non-negative integer n , an n -dimensional local field is a complete discrete valuation field whose residue field is an $(n-1)$ -dimensional local field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] Depending on the definition of local field, a *zero-dimensional local field* is then either a finite field (with the definition used in this article), or a perfect field of positive characteristic.
[src:p-adic-analysis/local-field] From the geometric point of view, n -dimensional local fields with last finite residue field are naturally associated to a complete flag of subschemes of an n -dimensional arithmetic scheme.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] In number theory, **Ostrowski's theorem**, due to Alexander Ostrowski (1916), states that every non-trivial absolute value on the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ is equivalent to either the usual real absolute value or a p-adic absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] This is sometimes written with a subscript 1 instead of infinity.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Ostrowski's theorem then states that if $|\cdot |_{*}:\mathbb {Q} \to \mathbb {R}$ is any absolute value on the rational numbers, then either $|\cdot |_{*}=|\cdot |_{0}$ , or $|\cdot |_{*}$ is equivalent to $|\cdot |$ , or $|\cdot |_{*}$ is equivalent to $|\cdot |_{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] The following proof follows the one of Theorem 10.1 in Schikhof (2007).
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Let $|\cdot |_{*}$ be an absolute value on the rationals.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] We start the proof by showing that it is entirely determined by the values it takes on prime numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] From the fact that $1\times 1=1$ and the multiplicativity property of the absolute value, we infer that $|1|_{*}^{2}=|1|_{*}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] In other words, the absolute value of a negative integer coincides with that of its opposite.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] There exist two coprime positive integers p and q such that $r=pq^{-1}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Altogether, the absolute value of a positive rational is entirely determined from that of its numerator and denominator.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Finally, let $\mathbb {P}$ be the set of prime numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] where $v_{p}(n)$ is the p-adic valuation of n.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] For all integer n, one has $|n|_{*}\leq 1$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Suppose that there exists a positive integer n such that $|n|_{*}>1.$ Let k be a non-negative integer and b be a positive integer greater than 1 .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] We express $n^{k}$ in base b: there exist a positive integer m and integers $(c_{i})_{0\leq i<m}$ such that for all i, $0\leq c_{i}<b$ and $n^{k}=\sum _{i<m}c_{i}b^{i}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] As a result, all integers greater than one have an absolute value strictly greater than one.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] By symmetry, this inequality is an equality.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Because the triangle inequality implies that for all positive integers n we have $|n|_{*}\leq n$ , in this case we obtain more precisely that $0<\lambda \leq 1$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] As per the above result on the determination of an absolute value by its values on the prime numbers, we easily see that $|r|_{*}=|r|_{\infty }^{\lambda }$ for all rational r, thus demonstrating equivalence to the real absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Suppose that for all integer n, one has $|n|_{*}\leq 1$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] As our absolute value is non-trivial, there must exist a positive integer n for which $|n|_{*}<1.$ Decomposing $|n|_{*}$ on the prime numbers shows that there exists $p\in \mathbb {P}$ such that $|p|_{*}<1$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] We claim that in fact this is so for one prime number only.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Suppose *by way of contradiction* that p and q are two distinct primes with absolute value strictly less than 1.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] This means that there exists a unique prime p such that $|p|_{*}<1$ and that for all other primes q, one has $|q|_{*}=1$ (from the hypothesis of this second case).
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] Another theorem states that any field, complete with respect to an Archimedean absolute value, is (algebraically and topologically) isomorphic to either the real numbers or the complex numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/ostrowski-s-theorem] This is sometimes also referred to as Ostrowski's theorem.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] In mathematics, ***p*-adic analysis** is a branch of number theory that studies functions of *p*-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Along with the more classical fields of real and complex analysis, which deal, respectively, with functions on the real and complex numbers, it belongs to the discipline of mathematical analysis.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] The theory of complex-valued numerical functions on the *p*-adic numbers is part of the theory of locally compact groups (abstract harmonic analysis).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] The usual meaning taken for *p*-adic analysis is the theory of *p*-adic-valued functions on spaces of interest.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Applications of *p*-adic analysis have mainly been in number theory, where it has a significant role in diophantine geometry and diophantine approximation.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Some applications have required the development of *p*-adic functional analysis and spectral theory.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] In many ways *p*-adic analysis is less subtle than classical analysis, since the ultrametric inequality means, for example, that convergence of infinite series of *p*-adic numbers is much simpler.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Topological vector spaces over *p*-adic fields show distinctive features; for example aspects relating to convexity and the Hahn–Banach theorem are different.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Ostrowski's theorem, due to Alexander Ostrowski (1916), states that every non-trivial absolute value on the rational numbers **Q** is equivalent to either the usual real absolute value or a p-adic absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] In any field of characteristic 0, one has the following result.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] is the *k*th binomial coefficient polynomial.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Over the field of real numbers, the assumption that the function *f* is a polynomial can be weakened, but it cannot be weakened all the way down to mere continuity.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] More generally it is used as a generic name for analogues for complete commutative rings (including *p*-adic fields in particular) of the Newton method for solving equations.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Since *p*-adic analysis is in some ways simpler than real analysis, there are relatively easy criteria guaranteeing a root of a polynomial.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] To state the result, let $f(x)$ be a polynomial with integer (or *p*-adic integer) coefficients, and let *m*,*k* be positive integers such that *m* ≤ *k*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] Helmut Hasse's local–global principle, also known as the Hasse principle, is the idea that one can find an integer solution to an equation by using the Chinese remainder theorem to piece together solutions modulo powers of each different prime number.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] This is handled by examining the equation in the completions of the rational numbers: the real numbers and the *p*-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-analysis] A more formal version of the Hasse principle states that certain types of equations have a rational solution if and only if they have a solution in the real numbers *and* in the *p*-adic numbers for each prime *p*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Every rational number can be uniquely expressed as the sum of a series as above, with respect to the p-adic absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This allows considering rational numbers as special p-adic numbers, and alternatively defining the p-adic numbers as the completion of the rational numbers for the p-adic absolute value, exactly as the real numbers are the completion of the rational numbers for the usual absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] p-adic numbers were first described by Kurt Hensel in 1897, though, with hindsight, some of Ernst Kummer's earlier work can be interpreted as implicitly using p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Roughly speaking, modular arithmetic modulo a positive integer n consists of "approximating" every integer by the remainder of its division by n, called its *residue modulo* n.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The main property of modular arithmetic is that the residue modulo n of the result of a succession of operations on integers is the same as the result of the same succession of operations on residues modulo n.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] When studying Diophantine equations, it's sometimes useful to reduce the equation modulo a prime p, since this usually provides more insight about the equation itself.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Unfortunately, doing this loses some information because the reduction $\mathbb {Z} \twoheadrightarrow \mathbb {Z} /p$ is not injective.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] One way to preserve more information is to use larger moduli, such as higher prime powers, *p*2, *p*3, ....
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] However, this has the disadvantage of $\mathbb {Z} /p^{e}$ not being a field, which loses a lot of the algebraic properties that $\mathbb {Z} /p$ has.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Kurt Hensel discovered a method which consists of using a prime modulus p, and applying Hensel's lemma to lift solutions modulo p to modulo *p*2, *p*3, ....
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This process creates an infinite sequence of residues, and a p-adic number is defined as the "limit" of such a sequence.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Essentially, p-adic numbers allows "taking modulo *p**e* for all e at once".
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] A distinguishing feature of p-adic numbers from ordinary modulo arithmetic is that the set of p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ forms a field, making division by p possible (unlike when working modulo *p**e*).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Furthermore, the mapping $\mathbb {Z} \hookrightarrow \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ is injective, so not much information is lost when reducing to p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] There are multiple ways to understand p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] One way to think about p-adic integers is using "base p".
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Informally, **p-adic integers** can be thought of as integers in base-p, but the digits extend *infinitely to the left*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Addition and multiplication on p-adic integers can be carried in a way somewhat similar to integers in base-p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] When adding together two p-adic integers, for example $\ldots 012102_{3}+\ldots 101211_{3}$ , their digits are added with carries being propagated from right to left.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Multiplication of p-adic integers works similarly via long multiplication.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Since addition and multiplication can be performed with p-adic integers, they form a ring, denoted $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ or $\mathbf {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Note that some rational numbers can also be p-adic integers, even if they aren't integers in a real sense.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] However, some rational numbers, such as ${\tfrac {1}{p}}$ , cannot be written as a p-adic integer.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Equivalently, every p-adic number is of the form ${\tfrac {x}{p^{k}}}$ , where x is a p-adic integer.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] For any nonzero p-adic number x, its multiplicative inverse ${\tfrac {1}{x}}$ is also a p-adic number, which can be computed using a variant of long division.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] For this reason, the p-adic numbers form a field, denoted $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ or $\mathbf {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] satisfying the compatibility relations $x_{i}\equiv x_{j}~(\operatorname {mod} p^{i})$ for $i<j$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This is equivalent to the base-p definition, because the last k digits of a base-p expansion uniquely define its value mod p*k*, and vice versa.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This form can also explain why some rational numbers are p-adic integers, even if they are not integers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] For example, ⁠1/5⁠ is a 3-adic integer, because its 3-adic expansion consists of the multiplicative inverses of 5 mod 3, 32, 33, ...
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] There are several equivalent definitions of p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The two approaches given below are relatively elementary.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] A **p-adic unit** is a p-adic integer whose first digit is nonzero, i.e. $a_{0}\neq 0$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The set of all p-adic integers is usually denoted $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Equivalently, a p-adic number is anything of the form ${\tfrac {x}{p^{k}}}$ , where x is a p-adic integer.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The first index v for which the digit $a_{v}$ is nonzero in r is called the p-adic valuation of r, denoted $v_{p}(r)$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] If $r=0$ , then such an index does not exist, so by convention $v_{p}(0)=\infty$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In this definition, addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division of p-adic numbers are carried out similarly to numbers in base p, with "carries" or "borrows" moving from left to right rather than right to left.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Division of p-adic numbers may also be carried out "formally" via division of formal power series, with some care about having to "carry".
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] With these operations, the set of p-adic numbers form a field, denoted $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The p-adic numbers may also be defined as equivalence classes, in a similar way as the definition of real numbers as equivalence classes of Cauchy sequences.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The exponent v is uniquely determined by r and is called its **p-adic valuation**, denoted $v_{p}(r)$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The proof of the lemma results directly from the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] A **p-adic series** is a formal Laurent series of the form $\sum _{i=v}^{\infty }r_{i}p^{i},$ where v is a (possibly negative) integer and the $r_{i}$ are rational numbers that either are zero or have a nonnegative valuation (that is, the denominator of $r_{i}$ is not divisible by p).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Every rational number may be viewed as a p-adic series with a single nonzero term, consisting of its factorization of the form $p^{k}{\tfrac {m}{n}},$ with m and n both coprime with p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In the latter case, the series is called the *zero series*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Every p-adic series is equivalent to exactly one normalized series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This normalized series is obtained by a sequence of transformations, which are equivalences of series; see § Normalization of a p-adic series, below.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In other words, the equivalence of p-adic series is an equivalence relation, and each equivalence class contains exactly one normalized p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The usual operations of series (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) are compatible with equivalence of p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] With this, the **p-adic numbers** are defined as the *equivalence classes* of p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The uniqueness property of normalization, allows uniquely representing any p-adic number by the corresponding normalized p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Starting with the series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=v}^{\infty }r_{i}p^{i},}$ we wish to arrive at an equivalent series such that the p-adic valuation of $r_{v}$ is zero.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] For that, one considers the first nonzero $r_{i}.$ If its p-adic valuation is zero, it suffices to change v into i, that is to start the summation from v.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Then, if the series is not normalized, consider the first nonzero $r_{i}$ that is not an integer in the interval $[0,p-1].$ Using Bézout's lemma, write this as $r_{i}=a_{i}+ps_{i}$ , where $a_{i}\in [0,p-1]$ and $s_{i}$ has nonnegative valuation.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Then, one gets an equivalent series by replacing $r_{i}$ with $a_{i},$ and adding $s_{i}$ to $r_{i+1}.$ Iterating this process, possibly infinitely many times, provides eventually the desired normalized p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Other equivalent definitions use completion of a discrete valuation ring (see § p-adic integers), completion of a metric space (see § Topological properties), or inverse limits (see § Modular properties).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] A p-adic number can be defined as a *normalized p-adic series*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Since there are other equivalent definitions that are commonly used, one says often that a normalized p-adic series *represents* a p-adic number, instead of saying that it *is* a p-adic number.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] One can say also that any p-adic series represents a p-adic number, since every p-adic series is equivalent to a unique normalized p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This is useful for defining operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) of p-adic numbers: the result of such an operation is obtained by normalizing the result of the corresponding operation on series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This well defines operations on p-adic numbers, since the series operations are compatible with equivalence of p-adic series.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] With these operations, p-adic numbers form a field called the **field of *p*-adic numbers** and denoted $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ or $\mathbf {Q} _{p}.$ There is a unique field homomorphism from the rational numbers into the p-adic numbers, which maps a rational number to its p-adic expansion.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The image of this homomorphism is commonly identified with the field of rational numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This allows considering the *p*-adic numbers as an extension field of the rational numbers, and the rational numbers as a subfield of the *p*-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The *valuation* of a nonzero p-adic number x, commonly denoted $v_{p}(x),$ is the exponent of p in the first nonzero term of every p-adic series that represents x.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] By convention, $v_{p}(0)=\infty ;$ that is, the valuation of zero is $\infty .$ This valuation is a discrete valuation.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The restriction of this valuation to the rational numbers is the p-adic valuation of $\mathbb {Q} ,$ that is, the exponent v in the factorization of a rational number as ${\tfrac {n}{d}}p^{v},$ with both n and d coprime with p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] There are several different conventions for writing p-adic expansions.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] So far this article has used a notation for p-adic expansions in which powers of p increase from right to left.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] When performing arithmetic in this notation, digits are carried to the left.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] It is also possible to write p-adic expansions so that the powers of p increase from left to right, and digits are carried to the right.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] p-adic expansions may be written with other sets of digits instead of {0, 1, ..., *p* − 1}.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In fact any set of p integers which are in distinct residue classes modulo p may be used as p-adic digits.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In number theory, Teichmüller representatives are sometimes used as digits.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The p-*adic expansion* of a rational number can be computed similarly, but with a different division step.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Suppose that $r={\tfrac {n}{d}}$ is a rational number with nonnegative valuation (that is, d is not divisible by p).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The division step consists of writing $r=a+p\,r'$ where a is an integer such that $0\leq a<p,$ and $r'$ has nonnegative valuation.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The integer a can be computed as a modular multiplicative inverse: $a=nd^{-1}\operatorname {mod} p$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Because of this, writing r in this way is always possible, and such a representation is unique.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The p-adic expansion of a rational number is eventually periodic.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Conversely, a series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=k}^{\infty }a_{i}p^{i},}$ with $0\leq a_{i}<p$ converges (for the p-adic absolute value) to a rational number if and only if it is eventually periodic; in this case, the series is the p-adic expansion of that rational number.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The proof is similar to that of the similar result for repeating decimals.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The **p-adic integers** are the p-adic numbers with a nonnegative valuation.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Every integer is a p -adic integer (including zero, since $0<\infty$ ).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The rational numbers of the form ${\textstyle {\tfrac {n}{d}}p^{k}}$ with d coprime with p and $k\geq 0$ are also p -adic integers (for the reason that d has an inverse mod $p^{e}$ for every e ).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The p-adic integers form a commutative ring, denoted $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ or $\mathbf {Z} _{p}$ , that has the following properties.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The last property provides a definition of the p-adic numbers that is equivalent to the above one: the field of the p-adic numbers is the field of fractions of the completion of the localization of the integers at the prime ideal generated by p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The p-adic valuation allows defining an absolute value on p-adic numbers: the p-adic absolute value of a nonzero p-adic number x is $|x|_{p}=p^{-v_{p}(x)},$ where $v_{p}(x)$ is the p-adic valuation of x.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] As a metric space, the p-adic numbers form the completion of the rational numbers equipped with the p-adic absolute value.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This provides another way for defining the p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] As the metric is defined from a discrete valuation, every open ball is also closed.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This implies that the p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ form a locally compact space (locally compact field), and the p-adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ —that is, the ball $B_{1}[0]=B_{p}(0)$ —form a compact space.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The space of 2-adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{2}$ is homeomorphic to the Cantor set ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The Pontryagin dual of the group of p-adic integers is the Prüfer p-group $\mathbb {Z} (p^{\infty })$ , and the Pontryagin dual of the Prüfer p-group is the group of p-adic integers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The inverse limit of the rings $\mathbb {Z} _{p}/p^{n}\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ is defined as the ring formed by the sequences $a_{0},a_{1},\ldots$ such that $a_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} /p^{i}\mathbb {Z}$ and ${\textstyle a_{i}\equiv a_{i+1}{\pmod {p^{i}}}}$ for every i.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The mapping that maps a normalized p-adic series to the sequence of its partial sums is a ring isomorphism from $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ to the inverse limit of the $\mathbb {Z} _{p}/p^{n}\mathbb {Z} _{p}.$ This provides another way for defining p-adic integers (up to an isomorphism).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This definition of p-adic integers is specially useful for practical computations, as allowing building p-adic integers by successive approximations.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The same method can be used for computing the p-adic square root of an integer that is a quadratic residue modulo p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This seems to be the fastest known method for testing whether a large integer is a square: it suffices to test whether the given integer is the square of the value found in $\mathbb {Z} _{p}/p^{n}\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Applying Newton's method to find the square root requires ${\textstyle p^{n}}$ to be larger than twice the given integer, which is quickly satisfied.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Hensel lifting is a similar method that allows to "lift" the factorization modulo p of a polynomial with integer coefficients to a factorization modulo ${\textstyle p^{n}}$ for large values of n.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This is commonly used by polynomial factorization algorithms.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Both $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ and $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ are uncountable and have the cardinality of the continuum.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The field $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ contains $\mathbb {Q}$ and is a field of characteristic 0.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Because 0 can be written as sum of squares, $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ cannot be turned into an ordered field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The field of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ has only a single proper algebraic extension: the complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In other words, this quadratic extension is already algebraically closed.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] By contrast, the algebraic closure of $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ , denoted ${\overline {\mathbb {Q} _{p}}},$ has infinite degree, that is, $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ has infinitely many inequivalent algebraic extensions.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Also contrasting the case of real numbers, although there is a unique extension of the p-adic valuation to ${\overline {\mathbb {Q} _{p}}},$ the latter is not (metrically) complete.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Its (metric) completion is denoted $\mathbb {C} _{p}$ or $\Omega _{p}$ , and sometimes called the **complex p-adic numbers** by analogy to the complex numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The field $\mathbb {C} _{p}$ is algebraically closed.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] However, unlike $\mathbb {C}$ , this field is not locally compact.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The fields $\mathbb {C} _{p}$ and $\mathbb {C}$ are isomorphic, so we may regard $\mathbb {C} _{p}$ as $\mathbb {C}$ endowed with an exotic metric.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The proof of existence of such a field isomorphism relies on the axiom of choice, and does not provide an explicit example of such an isomorphism (that is, it is not constructive).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] If K is any finite Galois extension of $\mathbb {Q} _{p},$ the Galois group $\operatorname {Gal} \left(K/\mathbb {Q} _{p}\right)$ is solvable.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Thus, the absolute Galois group ${\operatorname {Gal} }{\bigl (}\,{\overline {\mathbb {Q} _{p}}}/\mathbb {Q} _{p}{\bigr )}$ is prosolvable.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The unit group $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ is contained in the multiplicative group $\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times }=\mathbb {Q} _{p}-\{0\}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] They have the same torsion subgroup (subgroup of elements of finite order).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Hensel's lemma implies that the torsion subgroup of $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ maps surjectively to $\mathbb {F} _{p}^{\times }$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] In particular, the torsion subgroup of $\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times }$ is cyclic of order $p-1$ when $p>2$ , and equals $\{\pm 1\}$ when $p=2$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Therefore, for *n* > 2, the field $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ contains the nth cyclotomic field if and only if *n* | *p* − 1.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Given a natural number k, let $\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times k}$ be the group of *k*th powers of elements of $\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times }$ ; then the index $(\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times }:\mathbb {Q} _{p}^{\times k})$ is finite.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Helmut Hasse's local–global principle is said to hold for an equation if it can be solved over the rational numbers if and only if it can be solved over the real numbers and over the p-adic numbers for every prime p.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This principle holds, for example, for equations given by quadratic forms, but fails for higher polynomials in several indeterminates.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The *p*-adic numbers have appeared in several fields of mathematics as well as physics.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Similar to the more classical fields of real and complex analysis, which deal, respectively, with functions on the real and complex numbers, ***p*-adic analysis** studies functions on *p*-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Two important concepts from *p*-adic analysis are Mahler's theorem, which characterizes every continuous *p*-adic function in terms of polynomials, and Volkenborn integral, which provides a method of integration for *p*-adic functions.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The reals and the p-adic numbers are the completions of the rationals; it is also possible to complete other fields, for instance general algebraic number fields, in an analogous way.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Suppose *D* is a Dedekind domain and *E* is its field of fractions.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] If *x* is a non-zero element of *E*, then *xD* is a fractional ideal and can be uniquely factored as a product of positive and negative powers of non-zero prime ideals of *D*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The choice of *c* does not change the completion (different choices yield the same concept of Cauchy sequence, so the same completion).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] It is convenient, when the residue field *D*/*P* is finite, to take for *c* the size of *D*/*P*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] For example, when *E* is a number field and *D* is its ring of integers, Ostrowski's theorem says that every non-trivial non-Archimedean absolute value on *E* arises as some |⋅|*P*.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The remaining non-trivial absolute values on *E* arise from the different embeddings of *E* into the real or complex numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] Often, one needs to simultaneously keep track of all the above-mentioned completions when *E* is a number field (or more generally a global field), which are seen as encoding "local" information.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] This is accomplished by adele rings and idele groups.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-number] The Chinese remainder theorem likewise implies a structure of $\mathbb {Z} _{n}$ for composite bases: for any *n* which has at least two distinct prime factors, the *n*-adic integer ring $\mathbb {Z} _{n}$ is isomorphic to $\prod _{p|n}\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] In number theory, the **p-adic valuation** or **p-adic order** of an integer n is the exponent of the highest power of the prime number p that divides n.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] Equivalently, $\nu _{p}(n)$ is the exponent to which p appears in the prime factorization of n .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] The p-adic valuation is a valuation and gives rise to an analogue of the usual absolute value, though unlike the latter, the p-adic absolute value is not Archimedean.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] Whereas the completion of the rational numbers with respect to the usual absolute value results in the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , the completion of the rational numbers with respect to the p-adic absolute value results in the p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] where $\mathbb {N} _{0}$ denotes the set of natural numbers (including zero) and $m\mid n$ denotes divisibility of n by m .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] The notation $p^{k}\parallel n$ is sometimes used to mean $k=\nu _{p}(n)$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] If n is a positive integer, then $\nu _{p}(n)\leq \log _{p}n$ ; this follows directly from $n\geq p^{\nu _{p}(n)}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] where $\min$ is the minimum (i.e. the smaller of the two).
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] The p-adic absolute value satisfies the following properties.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] where the product is taken over all primes p and the usual absolute value, denoted $|r|_{0}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] This follows from simply taking the prime factorization: each prime power factor $p^{k}$ contributes its reciprocal to its p-adic absolute value, and then the usual Archimedean absolute value cancels all of them.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] By Ostrowski's theorem, the usual and p-adic absolute values occurring in the formula are all the absolute values on the rational numbers up to equivalence.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] An analogous product formula can be used to axiomatically define global fields, of which the rational numbers are the simplest example.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] The completion of $\mathbb {Q}$ with respect to this metric leads to the set $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ of p-adic numbers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/p-adic-valuation] Like the rationals, they form a field, and the p-adic valuation and absolute value can be extended to $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ , making it a complete valued field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] where the inverse limit of the quotient rings $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ runs through all natural numbers n , partially ordered by divisibility.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] By definition, this ring is the profinite completion of the integers $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] where the index p runs over all prime numbers, and $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ is the ring of *p*-adic integers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] This group is important because of its relation to Galois theory, étale homotopy theory, and the ring of adeles.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] In addition, it provides a basic tractable example of a profinite group.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Pointwise addition and multiplication make it a commutative ring.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Every integer $n\geq 0$ has a unique representation in the factorial number system as $n=\sum _{i=1}^{\infty }c_{i}i!\quad {\text{with }}c_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} ,$ where $0\leq c_{i}\leq i$ for every i , and only finitely many of $c_{1},c_{2},c_{3},\ldots$ are nonzero.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] In the same way, a profinite integer can be uniquely represented in the factorial number system as an infinite string $(\cdots c_{3}c_{2}c_{1})_{!}$ , where each $c_{i}$ is an integer satisfying $0\leq c_{i}\leq i$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] The digits $c_{1},c_{2},c_{3},\ldots ,c_{k-1}$ determine the value of the profinite integer modulo $k!$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Another way to understand the construction of the profinite integers is by using the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Recall that for an integer n with prime factorization $n=p_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{a_{k}}$ of non-repeating primes, there is a ring isomorphism $\mathbb {Z} /n\cong \mathbb {Z} /p_{1}^{a_{1}}\times \cdots \times \mathbb {Z} /p_{k}^{a_{k}}$ from the theorem.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Moreover, any surjection $\mathbb {Z} /n\to \mathbb {Z} /m$ will just be a map on the underlying decompositions where there are induced surjections $\mathbb {Z} /p_{i}^{a_{i}}\to \mathbb {Z} /p_{i}^{b_{i}}$ since we must have $a_{i}\geq b_{i}$ .
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Under the inverse limit definition of the profinite integers, we have the isomorphism ${\widehat {\mathbb {Z} }}\cong \prod _{p}\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ with the direct product of *p*-adic integers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] The topology on each finite group $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ is given as the discrete topology.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] In fact, the Pontryagin dual of ${\widehat {\mathbb {Z} }}$ is the abelian group $\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ equipped with the discrete topology (note that it is not the subset topology inherited from $\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z}$ , which is not discrete).
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] The tensor product ${\widehat {\mathbb {Z} }}\otimes _{\mathbb {Z} }\mathbb {Q}$ is the ring of finite adeles $\mathbf {A} _{\mathbb {Q} ,f}={\prod _{p}}'\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ of $\mathbb {Q}$ , where the symbol ' indicates a restricted product.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] That is, an element is a sequence that is integral except at a finite number of places.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] For the algebraic closure ${\overline {\mathbf {F} }}_{q}$ of a finite field $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ of order *q,* the Galois group can be computed explicitly.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] This construction can be reinterpreted in many ways.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] One of them is from étale homotopy type, which defines the étale fundamental group $\pi _{1}^{et}(X)$ as the profinite completion of automorphisms $\pi _{1}^{et}(X)=\lim _{i\in I}{\text{Aut}}(X_{i}/X),$ where $X_{i}\to X$ is an étale cover.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Then, the profinite integers are isomorphic to the group $\pi _{1}^{et}({\text{Spec}}(\mathbf {F} _{q}))\cong {\widehat {\mathbb {Z} }}$ from the earlier computation of the profinite Galois group.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] If the algebraic torus is considered over a field k , then the étale fundamental group $\pi _{1}^{et}(\mathbb {G} _{m}/{\text{Spec(k)}})$ contains an action of ${\text{Gal}}({\overline {k}}/k)$ as well from the fundamental exact sequence in étale homotopy theory.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Class field theory is a branch of algebraic number theory studying the abelian field extensions of a field.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] Given the global field $\mathbb {Q}$ , the abelianization of its absolute Galois group ${\text{Gal}}({\overline {\mathbb {Q} }}/\mathbb {Q} )^{ab}$ is intimately related to the associated ring of adeles $\mathbb {A} _{\mathbb {Q} }$ and the group of profinite integers.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] In particular, there is a map, called the Artin map $\Psi _{\mathbb {Q} }:\mathbb {A} _{\mathbb {Q} }^{\times }/\mathbb {Q} ^{\times }\to {\text{Gal}}({\overline {\mathbb {Q} }}/\mathbb {Q} )^{ab},$ which is an isomorphism.
[src:p-adic-analysis/profinite-integer] There is an analogous statement for local class field theory since every finite abelian extension of $K/\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ is induced from a finite field extension $\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}/\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
